article.description:
Michael Beasley scored 30 points, most of
them during a critical second-half run, and No. 25 Kansas State
escaped an upset Sunday with a 76-66 victory over Pittsburg State.
article.headline: Beasley's encore performance leads K-State past Pittsburg St.
article.linkText: Beasley nets 30 as K-State topples Pittsburg St.
article.story: MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Michael Beasley proved he could set records in his Kansas State debut. On Sunday, he showed he can carry the team with the game on the line. Beasley scored 30 points, most of them during a critical second-half run, and Kansas State (No. 25 AP) escaped an upset with a 76-66 victory over Pittsburg State. The freshman forward also had 14 rebounds, posting his second double-double in as many games. He had 32 points and a Big 12 Conference-record 24 rebounds in the Wildcats' victory over Sacramento State on Friday night. Beasley, the most highly touted freshman in school history, scored 16 points over the final nine minutes Sunday, leading Kansas State (2-0) on a 26-9 spurt to close the game and avoid a loss to the Division II Gorillas. "He's a winner," Kansas State coach Frank Martin said. "That's what matters to him. He played like an 18-year-old today -- tired. He didn't go out there and play with tremendous energy." Martin is keeping Beasley and the rest of the Wildcats' newcomers from speaking with the media until further notice. Kansas State was playing its second game in three days because Martin wanted to prepare his young players with a tournament-like schedule. The Wildcats head to Orlando, Fla., in two weeks to play in the Old Spice Classic. The Wildcats appeared to be a bit tired all day shooting the ball, finishing 43 percent from the field and 4-of-19 from beyond the arc. It wasn't any better from the free-throw line, where Kansas State was just 14-of-27 (52 percent). The Wildcats stepped up their defense in the second half, particularly when Pittsburg State point guard Keith Windom fouled out with 6:47 left. The Gorillas committed 11 second-half turnovers, including six from backup point guard Aaron Jackson. The Gorillas shot 41 percent, but hit only one field goal in the final nine minutes. "I told everyone we needed to pick up the defense," Kansas State guard Blake Young said. "In the first half we were letting them get the ball wherever they wanted to. In the second half we came out and tried to mess that up a little bit and get some easy buckets." Cory Abercrombie had 25 points and seven rebounds for Pittsburg State, which led 40-38 at halftime and by as many as seven in the second half. Spencer Magana added 12 points on 3-for-5 shooting from 3-point range. Pittsburg State went on a 15-0 run in the middle of the second half to take a 57-50 lead, but that's when Beasley took over. His tip-in with 9:13 left sparked the decisive run, and Kansas State took the lead for good at 60-59 when Beasley scored on a fast-break layup. "That was a really big point in the game," Pittsburg State coach Gene Iba said. "I thought we were a little tired. When you are a little tired, covering a guy that's going to be playing for money next year is pretty tough to do." Kansas State redshirt freshman Bill Walker, who sat out the season-opener against Sacramento State with an injury, was the only other player in double figures for the Wildcats. He finished with 11 points, all in the first half. Walker, who played six games last season before tearing his anterior cruciate ligament, limped off the court near the end of the first half with cramps in his right calf. Trainers iced it on the bench at the beginning of the second half, and Walker returned to the locker room with 7:20 remaining. He reappeared a few minutes later and tried to check in on his way to the bench, but Martin immediately told him to sit down. "[Walker] is fine," Martin said. "He hadn't practiced in four days, and it was a high-intensity game and he just cramped up. The season is long, and I want guys to be able to play the whole season, not just one night." The contest was a regular-season game for the Wildcats, but it counted as Pittsburg State's final exhibition game.
